article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw had 25 points and five rebounds Thursday, leading the Washington Mystics to a 69-64 victory over the Indiana Fever.
article.headline: Fever's Catchings shoots just 5-of-19
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw is helping her Washington
Mystics teammates figure out their roles.

Holdsclaw, the only player among the WNBA's top five in scoring,
rebounding and steals, finished with 25 points and five rebounds
Thursday night, leading the Mystics to a 69-64 victory over the
Indiana Fever.

"I'm probably the worst person to ask that question because I'm
the type of person who believes you come to work, you do your
job," Holdsclaw said. "Everybody has a role, and we're figuring
it out.

"I think everybody knows what has to be done. We've talked
about it enough; it's just a matter of getting it done. The bottom
line is the stat sheet doesn't lie, and in a game like tonight we
had production across the board."

Muriel Page scored a season-high 11 points and hit back-to-back
jumpers with 2:51 remaining to give the Mystics a 60-56 lead.

Rookie Alana Beard, who added 10 points, four rebounds and three
blocks, made a jumper from the corner and a free throw in the final
minute to help secure the victory. Page punctuated the win by
drawing a charge on Tamika Catchings with 37 seconds left.

Catchings had 21 points to lead the Fever. Kelly Schumacher
added a season-high 17 points, and Kristen Rasmussen matched her
career-high with nine rebounds.

"One of those nights and then some," said Catchings, who shot
5-for-19. "I think a lot of it is my fault for missing layups,
which kind of opened the door for my teammates to miss layups,
which is not acceptable."

Mystics coach Michael Adams believes his team is making
progress.

"Our goal is to hit the .500 mark for the season," he said.
"We need to win ... and make some noise in the East. The East is
wide open."

Catchings converted four straight free throws to pull the Fever
within 56-54 with 4:21 left. Schumacher added two more free throws,
extending Indiana's streak to 10 straight from the line, as the
Fever tied the game at 56-all with 3:52 remaining.

"We outrebounded them and had less turnovers," Fever coach
Brian Winters said. "We did everything right other than shoot the
ball. We probably missed eight or 10 layups from point-blank range,
so tonight was a bit of a struggle. We finish some of those and it
might have been a different outcome."

The Fever failed to make a field goal from the 9:19 mark until
12 seconds remained, when Stephanie White hit a 3-pointer.

Holdsclaw's three-point play gave the Mystics a 48-44 lead with
10:04 remaining.

Washington opened the second half with a 6-0 run, capped by
Beard's jumper that extended the lead to 36-32.

"We can't have key people who we need to show up giving us
doughnuts," Holdsclaw said. "I know it's tough, but we have to
stick together. Every night that I come here, I have to do my job.
I have to rebound and create for this team just to score, and
that's a lot of pressure in itself. Sometimes I feel like if you
can just accept your role and what you have to bring to this team,
it may be a mission, but we're going to get it done.

"It's tough to win with a one-woman team. When you win like
tonight, it's really rewarding. It feels good going home because
everybody contributed."
